\label{sect:dpg}

The derived Picard group ${\mathrm{DPic}}(A)$ of an algebra $A$ was introduced independently by Yekutieli and Rouquier-Zimmermann~\cite{yekutieli99,rouquierzimmerman03}.  This group can be defined succinctly as the collection of isoclassses of invertible objects in the monoidal category $(D^b(A{\otimes} A^{op}),{\otimes}^{{\mathrm{L}}}_A)$.  Or rather, it is the group of isoclasses of {\it tilting complexes} for $A$.  Via Rickard's study of derived equivalences~\cite{rickard91}, one finds that the derived Picard group is a derived invariant in the sense that any $k$-linear triangulated equivalence $D^b(A)\overset{\sim}\to D^b(B)$ implies an isomorphism of groups ${\mathrm{DPic}}(A)\cong{\mathrm{DPic}}(B)$, provided both $A$ and $B$ are projective over $k$.
